content.text: JavaScript Object Properties
An Object is an Unordered Collection of Properties
Properties are the most important part of JavaScript objects.
content.html: Properties are the most important part of JavaScript objects.

content.text: Properties can be changed, added, deleted, and some are read only.
content.html: Properties can be changed, added, deleted, and some are read only.

content.text: Accessing JavaScript Properties
The syntax for accessing the property of an object is:
content.html: The syntax for accessing the property of an object is:

content.code_html:
// objectName.property
 let age = person.age;

content.text: or

content.code_html:
//objectName["property"]
 let age = person["age"];

content.text: or

content.code_html:
//objectName[expression]
 let age = person[x];
person.firstname + " is " + person.age + " years old.";

content.text: Adding New Properties
You can add new properties to an existing object by simply giving it a value:
content.html: You can add new properties to an existing object by simply giving it a value:

content.code_html: person.nationality = "English";

content.text: Deleting Properties
The delete keyword deletes a property from an object:
content.html: The delete keyword deletes a property from an object:

content.code_html:
const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  age: 50,
  eyeColor: "blue"
};

delete person.age;

content.text: or delete person["age"];

content.code_html:
const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  age: 50,
  eyeColor: "blue"
};

delete person["age"];

content.text: Note:
The delete keyword deletes both the value of the property and the property itself.
content.html: The delete keyword deletes both the value of the property and the property itself.

content.text: After deletion, the property cannot be used before it is added back again.
content.html: After deletion, the property cannot be used before it is added back again.

content.text: Nested Objects
Property values in an object can be other objects:
content.html: Property values in an object can be other objects:

content.code_html:
myObj = {
  name:"John",
  age:30,
  myCars: {
    car1:"Ford",
    car2:"BMW",
    car3:"Fiat"
  }
}

content.text: You can access nested objects using the dot notation or the bracket notation:
content.html: You can access nested objects using the dot notation or the bracket notation:

content.code_html: myObj.myCars.car2;
